============ Patient Management System ============

Overview:

This project simulates a patient management system which would be used in a medical clinic. This system manages two
main features:

1. Patient History - historical records of patient visits
2. Waiting Room - a queue of patients waiting to be seen

Two data structures are used to implement this system:

1. Queue (FIFO) - used in the waiting room service
2. Doubly Linked List (DLL) - used in the patient history service

Why a Queue (FIFO) is appropriate for Waiting Room service?

A Queue is an ideal data structure for managing a waiting room because it follows the First-In-First-Out (FIFO)
principle. In a medical clinic, patients are normally seen in the same order they arrive. The queue structure naturally
models this behavior.

Operations used in the waiting room include:

- Add Patient → Patient joins the end of the queue.
- Serve Next Patient → The patient at the front of the queue is removed and served.
- Emergency Insertion → Allows inserting a patient at a specific position when necessary.

Using a queue ensures the waiting room behaves in a fair and predictable order and protects against duplicate entries.

FIFO Principle

FIFO stands for First-In-First-Out. This means that the first element inserted into the queue will be the
first one removed.

Example:

Patient arrival order - 1. Alice 2. Billy 3. Charlie
Queue structure - Front → Alice → Billy → Charlie → Back
When the doctor calls a patient - Alice is served first
Then Alice is removed - Front → Billy → Charlie → Back

This system ensures patients are treated in the order they arrived.

What would happen if a stack was used instead of a queue?

A stack follows the last in first out (LIFO) principle, this means the last patient to arrive would be the first
to be seen by the doctor.

Example with stack:

Patient arrival order - 1. Alice 2. Billy 3. Charlie
Stack order - Top → Charlie → Billy → Alice
When the doctor calls a patient - Charlie is served first

This would create an unfair waiting system, because the newest patient would always jump ahead of earlier patients.
Therefor using a stack would be inappropriate for a medical clini system.

Why a doubly linked list is appropriate for Patient History service.

A Doubly Linked List (DLL) is used for patient history service because it allows efficient navigation in both directions
of the list.

Each node in a doubly linked list contains:

A reference to the next record
A reference to the previous record

This structure allows the system to:

Move forward through patient records
Move backward through patient records
Keep track of a current record

In the program, this is used to implement the history navigation menu, where users can move to the next or previous
record in the list. This behavior is similar to how users browse browser history or undo/redo functionality.


